```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Pressure_Sensor_Array -> Amplifier_Pressure [label="1 mV max"];
    Temperature_Sensor_Array -> Amplifier_Temperature [label="100 mV max"];
    Amplifier_Pressure -> Filter_Pressure;
    Amplifier_Temperature -> Filter_Temperature;
    Filter_Pressure -> Multiplexer;
    Filter_Temperature -> Multiplexer;
    Multiplexer -> ADC;
    ADC -> Computer;
}
```

```Explanations
Pressure_Sensor_Array: This block represents an array of 8 strain-gauge pressure sensors that provide an analog voltage output. Each sensor's output is conditioned to match the input requirements of the next stage, the amplifier. The sensors are sensitive enough to generate a maximum output of 1 mV under maximum pressure.

Amplifier_Pressure: This block amplifies the low-level signals from the pressure sensors to a level that can be more effectively processed and filtered. The amplification factor is set based on the ADC input voltage range and the maximum output of the pressure sensors.

Temperature_Sensor_Array: This block represents an array of 8 infrared radiation detectors used to measure surface temperature. Each sensor outputs an analog voltage signal with a maximum output of 100 mV.

Amplifier_Temperature: Similar to the pressure signal amplifier, this block amplifies the temperature sensor signals. The gain is chosen according to the ADC input requirements and the maximum output of the temperature sensors.

Filter_Pressure & Filter_Temperature: These blocks are low-pass filters designed to condition the signals from the pressure and temperature sensors, respectively. They remove high-frequency noise and prevent aliasing before the signals are sampled by the ADC. The filter cutoff frequencies should be chosen based on the sensor signal characteristics and the desired signal bandwidth.

Multiplexer: As the ADC is sampling one channel at a time, the multiplexer selects which sensor signal to pass through to the ADC at any given time. It sequentially connects each sensor output from the pressure and temperature arrays to the ADC input.

ADC: The analog-to-digital converter transforms the analog sensor signals into digital data that can be processed by a computer. The ADC sampling rate and resolution should be chosen based on the desired temporal resolution and accuracy of the measurements.

Computer: This block represents the computing system that receives the digitized sensor data for analysis and monitoring. The computer handles data storage, display, and any further processing or analysis as needed.
```

